.section Programming the TMB

It is assumed that the reader is familiar with the Acorn documentation for
podules ("A Series Podules", Acorn Computers, May 1987) and the Inmos data
sheet for the IMSC012 link adapter chip. All devices on the TMB are byte
wide and should therefore be accessed with byte (as opposed to word) cycles.

The TMB contains a podule identity (PI) ROM which is mapped into the PI
space. The ROM contains an extended (8 byte) PI as follows:
.
.tabset 10 20 35
.copy
.contig inline
.space
.
$t _Byte $t Content $t Comment_

$t 0 $t X'00' $t (X'01', X'04', X'05' )
$t 1 $t       $t (reserved)
$t 2 $t       $t (reserved)
$t 3 $t X'4B' $t Product type (low)
$t 4 $t X'00' $t Product type (high)
$t 5 $t X'0E' $t Manufacturer (low)
$t 6 $t X'00' $t Manufacturer (high)
$t 7 $t X'00' $t Country
.
.space
.endc
.fill
.
Bit 0 of byte 0 is a 1 when the TMB is generating an IRQ interrupt. Bit 2
of byte 0 is a 1 when the TMB is generating a FIQ interrupt.

The TMB is a Simple Podule and is thus accessed by cycles controlled by the
Archimedes' I/O controller chip. All devices on the TMB may be accessed
using fast cycles. In addition to the podule ID ROM the TMB contains an
Inmos C012 link adapter chip and a control/status
register (CSR). The four registers of the link adapter are mapped into
successive words in the I/O space and the CSR is mapped into the next word.
Thus, if the TMB is placed in podule slot 0 in the Archimedes the memory map
is as follows:
.
.copy
.contig inline
.space
.tabset 10 20 41c
.
$t _Address $t Content $t Access speed_

$t X'33C0000' $t PI byte 0    $t synchronous
$t X'33C0004' $t PI byte 1    $t "
$t . . .      $t . . .        $t "
$t X'33C001C' $t PI byte 7    $t "

$t X'3342000' $t C012 reg 0   $t fast
$t X'3342004' $t C012 reg 1   $t "
$t X'3342008' $t C012 reg 2   $t "
$t X'334200C' $t C012 reg 3   $t "
$t X'3342010' $t CSR          $t "
.
.space
.endc
.fill
.
This set of registers repeats at 8 word intervals throughout the podule
address space. To maintain compatability with future products of a similar
type, only the lowest set of addresses should be used.

The control status register contains 6 bits which may be written and one bit
which is read-only. The write bits are cleared to zero when the Archimedes'
reset line is asserted. When writing to the CSR, the unused bits  (6 to 7)
should be zero to maintain compatibility with other similar products.

The functions of the bits in this register are as follows

$bf Bit 0 - ResetOut$unbf. Writing a 1 asserts the reset line on the Host
control signal port.

$bf Bit 1 - AnalyseOut$unbf. Writing a 1 asserts the analyse line on 
the Host control signal port.

$bfBit 2 - LinkSpeed$unbf. Connected to the LinkSpeed pins of the link adapter
chip and the TRAMs. Writing a 1 causes the board to operate with a 20MHz link
speed. A zero causes a link speed of 10MHz.

$bfBit 3 - ChipReset$unbf. Writing a 1 asserts the reset line of the link
adapter chip. Normally asserted with ResetOut and may be useful if the chip
locks up because of a faulty link connection.

$bfBit 4 (READ) - ErrorIn$unbf. Reflects the state of the Error signal on the
Host control signal port. This bit is read-only and a 0 indicates the
presence of an error.

$bfBit 4 (WRITE) - IntMask$unbf. Writing a 1 allows the board to generate
interrupts. A 0 disables interrupt generation.

$bfBit 5 - IntType$unbf. Determines the type of interrupt generated by the
link adapter chip. A 0 generates IRQ interrupts while a 1 generates FIQ
interrupts when the link adapter has sent or received a byte.

The two interrupt signals of the link adapter chip are ORed together to
generate the IRQ or FIQ signal required by the Archimedes. Note that the 
host error signal always generates an IRQ interrupt.
.
